{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f1b40b90-4751-4d7c-a49f-e1b983b4840f","content":"**Best tool: `dotnet-trace`** (lightweight, .NET-specific, no restart needed).\n\n### Quick steps:\n\n```bash\n# 1. Install the tool (one-time)\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU profile (30 seconds is usually enough)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or **PerfView**.\n\n### Alternative: PerfView (deeper OS-level detail)\n\nIf you need kernel-level CPU stacks (e.g., native code, driver issues):\n\n```powershell\n# Download PerfView.exe from https://github.com/microsoft/perfview/releases\nPerfView.exe collect -ThreadTime -Duration:30\n```\n\n**TL;DR** — Start with `dotnet-trace` for managed code hot-path analysis. Escalate to PerfView if you suspect native/kernel contention.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bd1969f2-0493-4cc2-876b-970f3c280d3c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about diagnostics for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server with high CPU. This is a knowledge question — no code changes or repo exploration needed. I'll give a concise, actionable answer.","outputTokens":328,"requestId":"7651:277795:190DBF4:1C71C57:69FE8D46"},"id":"c3eff108-5096-41cf-bfc1-101addbfe296","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:26:39.338Z","parentId":"9c837474-322b-46fa-ba40-570b50017e9c"}
